Next morning

Get in loser we’re making NY style pizza in a home oven! I want to talk about my home oven setup, I have a custom baking steel that goes all the way across the top, on the bottom where I cook the pizza, I have another steel that allows heat to rise up on the sides, and a layer of 9 unglazed quarry tiles on top of that steel to create a double layer of thermal battery. You could do this with all glazed quarry tiles and it would probably only cost $50 or less. The key is an extra thick thermal battery on the bottom, and another one on top that goes all the way across to trap the heat between them. This creates a sandwich of heat. I preheat the oven for an hour or two, my ovens highest setting is 550f. This gets the cooking surface to upwards of 620f which mimics the performance of a ny style deck oven. The pizza cooks in 6 min. It’s crispy on the outside & soft & fluffy inside the crust. I kinda couldn’t believe how good it was & I have been using this setup for 8 years. Give it a try & tag me in your oven setups! And as for this ny style dough recipe?! It’s new under development so stay tuned for my updated ny dough, but in case you’re curious it’s a hybrid of instant yeast direct & sourdough indirect fermentation. Have a great monday!

Sicilian Grandma Dough Recipe
By: Anthony Falco

1000 grams [ 8 cups ]  of flour (80% high protein or bread flour and 20% freshly milled whole grain or whole wheat flour)
720 [ 2 ¾ cups ]  grams of cold water (65f)
100 grams [ 1/2 cups & 2 tbsp ] of sourdough starter or commercial yeast preferment; biga, sponge, or poolish (room temp 3-12 hours after feeding)
50 grams [ 4 ½  tbsp ] of extra virgin olive oil
30 grams [ 2 tbsp ] of sea salt

Preferment instructions (aka biga, sponge, poolish)
80 grams [½ cup] high protein or bread flour
70 grams [ 6 tbsp] water
0.5 gram [¼ teaspoon]  instant yeast 
In a bowl add room temperature water and instant yeast, mix together until dissolved. Add flour and mix vigorously until it completely comes together. Cover bowl and allow to sit at room temperature. Use anywhere from 3-15 hours before making pizza dough, as a substitute for sourdough starter.

Bakers Percentages 
100% flour
72% water
10% starter
5% extra virgin olive oil
3% sea salt

Weigh everything out separately, Mix flour & salt, mix starter and water, combine, add oil til everything comes together, rest 30 min mix again for 5-8 min. Then transfer to oiled container & stretch & fold ever 15 min for 2-3 hours. Shape & generously flour, move to oiled pan. Cover & rest for 3hrs, press doughs out & let rise covered for 10-18hrs depending on ambient temperature, top w tomato & olives, bake at 480 f for about 15min. Cut open & fill w 1lb of thinly sliced mortadella, two pieces of burrata, 20g of grated parmigiano, and 10g of pistachio powder. 

Cut & enter sandwich paradise!

Sunday Meatballs!! One of my favorite things to make and eat! These babies are all beef but you can use any meat you want, or even use a meat substitute of your choice. You can even make them on a weekday if you want. If you like this recipe, share it! And even better buy a copy of my cookbook Pizza Czar, it is super duper on sale on Amazon, or you can buy on our website signed. Enjoy the sights & sounds of Sunday dinner at the Falco-Rosen house.

Grassfed Beef 1.5lbs (optional extra fat whipped and added to beef)
Pecorino  40g
Parmigiano  40g
Salt  15g
Black pepper  5g
Calabrian chili paste  10g
Fennel seed  10g
Flat leaf parsley  15g
Whole milk  175g
Egg yolks  60g
Stale sourdough bread 100g
Sourdough breadcrumbs toasted 50g

Soak stale cubed bread in milk
Pulverize spices w spice grinder
Chop parsley fine
Add dry spices to meat & mix
And panade, parsley & yolks to meat & mix
Add cheese & breadcrumbs, mix
Ball up meatballs w olive oiled hands
Refrigerate for 2 hrs or overnight for more firm texture 

For sauce, mince shallots, yellow onion & garlic, cook in olive oil on medium heat, add pinch of sicilian oregano, and chili powder, cook until aromatic but not browned, just golden. Add crushed tomatoes @biancodinapolitomatoes . Cook for hr or two stirring frequently. Watch for helicopters. Blend w immersion blender. Add torn basil.

Bake meatballs for 20min at 325f add to sauce. Cook for a lil while.

Cook pasta, in this case we are using amazing new pasta from @frankiesspuntino Mezze Maniche. 

When pasta is almost done. Remove meatballs into separate bowl. Add pasta to sauce. Cook to al dente.

Serve separately or all together. Garnish with pecorino, parsley, breadcrumbs, olive oil, and fresh basil. 

Eat meatballs!!! Make friends! Save leftovers because they are even better the next day!

Some home pizza making from Skagit Valley Washington. Leaning into west coast ingredients here. Dough recipe was variation on my Sicilian Grandma recipe in Pizza Czar.

1000g flour 100% (50/50 ka organic bread & @cairnspringmills glacier peak directly from the mill!)
740g water 74% (50f) 
100g sourdough 10%(fed twice 1:1:1 used 3 hours after feed)
40g extra virgin olive oil 4% (@partannafoods)
29g 2.9% sea salt

Mixed flour & salt together 
Mixed sourdough & water
Hand mixed together, leaving out oil until wets & drys are fully combined 
Rest for 45 min
Mix for 5 min
Transfer to flat bottomed container w lid 
Stretch & fold every 30 min for 3 hours
Portioned 340g for 9inch
900g for 10x13 pan
Balled tight, floured well 
Transfer to lightly oiled pan
Rest 2 hours
Press out, cover & proof at 70f for 10hrs

Faccia di Vecchia, a food memory that has traversed oceans & generations. I was wandering through the streets of Cammarata, Sicily talking with my guide Enzo, he asked if I knew any Sicilian language words, I said a knew a few and one I threw out was the name of a bread my great grandmother used to make, Faccia di Vecchia, he got really excited and at that exact moment a small car was turning down the tiny cobblestone street. It was the baker! Delivering breads of all kinds including fresh baked Faccia Di Vecchia! Tomato, anchovies, pecorino, olive oil & breadcrumbs, it was new & nostalgic at the same time. This is the kind of spontaneous magic you will experience in Sicily. Join me next year for my @modernadventurists trip to Sicily & Rome ! Sept 2024, link in the bio!

The half red half white from @totonnospizza First off I will just say this pizza was spectacular, it’s smaller size than the pre pandemic setup, but still spectacular. Totonno’s has for many many years been my favorite pizza in New York City (if I had to reluctantly pick one only). I don’t get to eat this pizza that often, the hours are not super convenient & neither is the location, but the pizza is still incredible. The crust is charred lightly on the bottom, crisp on the outside, tender inside without too much chew. I absolutely love the sliced fresh mozzarella with sauce splotched on top technique, a calling card of first wave ny coal oven pizza. The white pie at Totonno’s in my opinion sets the standard of which all other are merely commentary, garlicy, with funky pecorino & golden rivers of olive oil between the fresh mozzarella. You still take your order from Louise “Cookie” Ciminieri and when you do you are interacting with a direct descendant of the first generation of Pizza makers in America, before her Grandfather Anthony Pero immigrated from Napoli there was no pizza in America. 🇺🇸🇮🇹

CARBONARA! My friends at Fra’ Mani recently sent me some of their new Guanciale, and so I thought let’s make some carbonara. There are no tricks here, this is just a classic ( or at least my idea of classic ) recipe. Guanciale, black pepper, pecorino, egg yolk, parm, and pasta. First we drop pasta, mezze maniche w cook time of 15min. I start the guanciale in a cold pan, and I don’t want it crispy, just want to render some fat & clarify the little pieces. Then we add some black pepper, remove the guanciale, and then add some starchy pasta water and reduce. When the pasta is just about al dente we drain into the pan, and finish cooking in water, pepper, fat in the pan. At this point we cut the heat off, and dump in our finely grated pecorino and vigorously emulsify and toss it until it’s a creamy consistency, at this point you have cacio e pepe! But now we add 3 egg yolks, and stir vigorously, then we add the guanciale back in and toss until it’s all nice and creamy, you can add more cheese or pasta water to control the consistency. And then finish with more freshly grated pecorino or parm & more fresh ground black pepper! Enjoy! 

Carbonara Recipe 
110 gram @frankiesspecialtyfoods Mezze Maniche
5 gram fresh ground black pepper 
55 gram  @eatframani guanciale 
3 egg yolk (pasture raised)
100 grams pecorino romano
20 grams parmigiano reggiano 
1/2 pint of pasta water
